04046nam a22005655i 9780520926042DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20012001cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209260427 a10.1525/97805209260422doi  a(DE-B1597)647669  a(OCoLC)1419790122  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aMUS0280002bisacsh1 aLetzter/Adelson, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWomen Writing Opera :bCreativity and Controversy in the Age of the French Revolution /cLetzter/Adelson; ed. by Jacqueline Letzter, Robert Adelson. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (358 p.) :b2 b/w photographs, 1 line illustration, 3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies on the History of Society and Culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART ONE -- tFigure -- t1. The Authors -- t2. Education -- t3. The Politics of Opera -- t4. Authority and Identity -- tPART TWO -- tFigure -- t5. The Career Manqué of Isabelle de Charrière: A Case Study -- tEpilogue: The Problem of the Exceptional Woman -- tAppendix: Operas by Women Composers and Librettists, 1670-1820 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the age of the French Revolution, opera was the locus of cabals, intrigues, and violent journalistic invective. Yet it was also a period when women composers and librettists gained access to concert halls as never before, some of their works among those most performed in Paris. Jacqueline Letzter and Robert Adelson's engaging history explains what made this possible. At the same time it demonstrates how the Revolution fostered many dreams and ambitions for women that would be doomed to disappointment in the repressive post-Revolutionary era.The first part of the book concentrates on the women who succeeded in bringing their operas to the stage. The authors examine their backgrounds, the institutional barriers they had to surmount, and the problems they faced in asserting their authority and authorship. The book's second half is a detailed case study of Isabelle de Charrière (1740–1805), a prolific author and composer who witnessed the success of her female colleagues but was unable to gain recognition for herself. In an analytical epilogue Letzter and Adelson discuss the status of creative women in Revolutionary culture and society.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aGenres & Styles. 4aMusic. 4aOpera. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Opera.2bisacsh1 aAdelson, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLetzter, Jacqueline, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022653140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092604240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520926042423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520926042/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles